                   SST are typical for recent decades. Maximum summer
                   salinities, likely set in the Bering Sea, remain
                   remarkably constant ({$\sim$}33.1 psu) over the
                   decade, elucidating the stable salinity of the
                   western Arctic cold halocline. Despite this,
                   freshwater flux variability (strongly driven by
                   transport) exceeds variability in other Arctic
                   freshwater sources. Remote data (winds, SST) prove
                   insufficient for quantifying variability, indicating
                   interannual change can still only be assessed by in
